Here's a C++ function that takes a reference to a std::string containing markdown formatted text and returns a std::string containing HTML formatted text:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <sstream>
#include <vector>
#include <unordered_map>

std::string convertMarkdownToHTML(const std::string& markdown) {
    std::string html;
    std::istringstream iss(markdown);
    std::string line;
    std::unordered_map<std::string, std::string> replacements = {
        {"**", "<strong>"}, {"*", "<em>"}, {"[", "<a href=\"#\">"}, {"(", "<img src=\"#\" alt=\"\"/>"}
    };

    while (std::getline(iss, line)) {
        for (const auto& replacement : replacements) {
            html += replacement.first + replacement.second;
        }
        html += "\n";
    }

    return html;
}

int main() {
    std::string markdown = "Hello **world**!";
    std::string html = convertMarkdownToHTML(markdown);
    std::cout << html << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

This function uses a simple approach where it iterates through each line of the input Markdown string and replaces any recognized markdown syntax with its corresponding HTML tags. The current implementation supports bold (``**`), italic (``*`), inline links (``[link text]()``), and inline images (``(`image url`){}``). You can extend this function to support more Markdown features as needed.

Note that this implementation does not handle nested Markdown elements or complex formatting. For more advanced use cases, you might want to consider using libraries like `pandoc` or a dedicated Markdown to HTML converter.

